SIMPLE: corrective
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Corrective
<hw>Cor*rect"ive</hw> <pr>(k?rr-r?k"t?v)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>correctif</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the power to correct; tending to rectify;
<as>as, <ex>corrective</ex> penalties</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mulberries are pectoral, <qex>corrective</qex> of billious
alkali.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Qualifying; limiting.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The Psalmist
interposeth . . . this <xex>corrective</xex> particle.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Holdsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Corrective</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Corrective
<hw>Cor*rect"ive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which has the
power of correcting, altering, or counteracting what is wrong or
injurious; <as>as, alkalies are <ex>correctives</ex> of acids; penalties
are <ex>correctives</ex> of immoral conduct</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Limitation; restriction.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Correctly</ent>⟦br⟧
